1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Nge2 Re8 {This is one of the most
flexible systems that Black could choose against 5.Nge2 system. Black intends
to meet 6.a3 by means of Bf8 and later on to follow with d7-d5 or c7-c5,
depending on the circumstances. My suggestion here is} 6. a3 Bf8 7. Ng3 {
I think that this move is White's best bet in the fight for an advantage. His
plan is to finish the development by playing Bd3 followed by 0-0. Later on,
White could consider gaining space on the queenside by means of b2-b4.} d5 {
By far the most logical continuation, Black fights for the centre and prepares
the c7-c5 advance in a suitable moment. Also, it's important to mention, 7...
d5 is designed to restrict White's c1 - bishop.} ({The continuation is rarely
seen in practice. White obtains a promising position after} 7... d6 {[%cal
Ge6e5]} 8. Bd3 e5 9. d5 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gf2f4] Followed by 0-0 and f2-f4. It's
important to remember that in such kind of positions, White has the important
e4-square for his knights. On the other hand, it's difficult to imagine how
Black could create an adequate counterplay.}) ({Dubious is the attempt to
enter Benoni type of positions after} 7... c5 $6 {since White develops a
dangerous initiative by means of} 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. b4 Bf8 10. Bb2 {[%cal Gf1d3]
In this position, White will continue his development by playing moves like
Bd3 and 0-0. Later on, Nce4 comes into consideration. With all these white
pieces which are directed against Black's king, various attacking ideas are
possible.}) 8. cxd5 {White want's to clarify the structure in the centre.
After the obvious 8...exd5, he is going to stop the c7-c5 advance by playing 9.
b2-b4. On the other hand, however, now Black's c8-bishop becomes active and
could be developed via e6 or g4.} ({Another interesting option is} 8. Be2 {
when the critical position arises after the moves} dxc4 9. O-O c5 {Black's
obvious intention is to simplify the position and equalize in a flawless way.
Nevertheless, the position arising after} 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Bxc4 {are far from
being simple. On the board, we have a position which is very similar to the
Queen's gambit accepted. Nevertheless, there are is an important difference -
while in QGA, White knight is on f3, here we have a knight on g3. I am
inclined to believe that in a number of positions, this difference is in
White's favor since very often in this structure White overtakes the
initiative by playing Ne4. This idea works extremely well in connection with
the move b2-b4 and Bb2. On the other hand, if White wants to execute his
another main idea connected with Qe2 followed by e3-e4-e5, then it's better to
have knight on f3 instead. This could be explained by the fact that a knight
on f3 would control the important d4-square, thus stopping Black's counterplay
based on the maneouvre Nc6-d4.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] This is the most
flexible continuation. Black's obvious idea is to follow with b7-b5 and Bb7.
It's important to remember that in such positions, the knight is usually
better placed on d7 than on c6.} ({The idea to execute the same idea after the
exchange of the queens is not so effective. For example, after} 11... Qxd1 12.
Rxd1 a6 {White could prevent Black from playing b7-b5 and Bb7 by means of} 13.
Be2 $1 {[%cal Ge2f3] Now 13...b5 would be met by 14.Bf3.} Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6]
Again with the idea to transfer the bishop to the long diagonal. Now, however,
White could use his lead in the development in order to obtain a pair of
bishops.} 14. Nge4 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Be7 16. Nd6 Bxd6 17. Rxd6 {Black's position
remains fairly solid but the bishop pair gives White small but lasting
advantage. Black's attempt to exchange the light-squared bishops doesn't work.
For example after} Bb5 18. Bf3 Bc6 {White could go for} 19. Bd1 Nd7 20. Bd2 $14
{In such kind of positions, White's main idea is to gain space on the kingisde
and in the same time to restrict the activity of Black's c6-bishop. That's why,
in the future, he could consider playing moves like f2-f3, e3-e4 followed by
g2-g4-g5 and h2-h4. Only by contacting opponent's kingside pawns, we could
increase the potential of our bishops.}) 12. Qe2 $146 {This flexible move
turns out to be a novelty. In his game against Kryvoruchko, Kuzubov played 12.
Be2 but failed to achieve an edge. With his last move, White keeps all the
options open. Depending on Black's plan, he could go for b2-b4 followed by Bb2
and Ne4 or gain space in the centre by means of e3-e4-e5. White is slightly
better developed which is very important in symmetrical positions.} b5 13. Rd1
Qc7 14. Bd3 Nbd7 15. Bd2 Bb7 16. Nce4 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gd2c3] Despite the fact
that Black's position remains fairly solid, White retains a small edge. Later
on, he coukd proceed with Rac1 followed by either Bc3 or Bb4. It is always
pleasant to play risk-free positions in which we could torture our opponent
for a long time.}) 8... exd5 9. b4 c6 10. Bd3 {We have reached the so-called
Carlsbad pawn structure. In such kind of poistions, White has two main ideas:
1) create a weakness on the queenside by means of b4-b5 followed by bxc6 2) go
for central strategy by playing f2-f3 followed by e3-e4. One of the main
drawbacks in White's position is the c1-bishop which is placed behind the
e3-d4 pawn chain. On the other hand, the g3-knight not only protects the
kingside but at the same time prevents Black from executing his typical
counterplay based on Ne4.} Na6 ({Another possibility is} 10... Nbd7 11. O-O a5
12. Rb1 axb4 13. axb4 Nb6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gb6c4] This is a very typical idea in
this structure. Black starts fighting for the weakened c4-square. His plan is
to play Be6 followed by Nc4 and b7-b5. Another imporant point to remember is
that Black must always be ready to meet b4-b5 by means of c6-c5.} 14. Qc2 Be6
15. Nce2 $1 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gd4c5,Gc2c5,Gb4b5] This is very imporant subtlety.
Before going for the normal b4-b5, White takes the control over the important
c5-square. At the same time, in a number of positions, White could consider
playing Nf4.} Bd6 {I think that this is not the most precise reaction since
Black is wasting a valuable time.} ({Instead, he should have played} 15... Nc4
{[%cal Gb7b5]} 16. b5 c5 17. dxc5 Rc8 18. c6 bxc6 19. bxc6 Rxc6 $11 {The
position is equal. The activity of Black's pieces compensates the slightly
inferior pawn structure.}) 16. b5 cxb5 17. Rxb5 Bd7 18. Rb1 g6 19. Qb3 {
White retains some advantage in this position. Black should constantly take
care of his weak pawns on d5 and b7.1/2-1/2 Baburin,A-Hussein,H/Dresden GER
2008/ The Week in Chess 734 (57)}) 11. O-O ({An interesting alternative would
have been} 11. b5 {Let's see how the game may continue.} Nc7 12. bxc6 bxc6 13.
O-O Rb8 14. Qc2 Ba6 $1 {This move is quite typical for the Carlsbad pawn
structure. For Black is important to exchange the light-squared bishops.} 15.
Bxa6 Nxa6 16. Na4 {In order to equalize, Black should realize the c6-c5 pawn
break. That's why the logical continuation is} Rc8 17. Bb2 c5 18. dxc5 Nxc5 19.
Nxc5 Rxc5 20. Qd3 {We have reached a typical IQP position. Given the fact that
some minor pieces are already exchanged and Black couldn't create a kingside
activity, White retains some edge.}) 11... Nc7 12. f3 {Given the fact that
Black is ready to meet b4-b5 by means of c6-c5, White changes his mind. He
goes for the another typical idea - e3-e4.} Ne6 13. Nce2 {[%cal Gd3c2,Ge3e4]
In order to realize e3-e4 advance, White should firstly protect the d4-pawn.
In this situation, he is planning to play Bc2 followed by e3-e4.} g6 14. Bc2 a5
15. Rb1 axb4 16. axb4 b6 {Black is planning to meet the central e3-e4 break by
means of c6-c5.} ({Despite the fact that Black's last move is positionally
sound, Black should have played against the slightly misplaced g3-knight.
Already, White should care about the equality.} 16... h5 $1 17. e4 h4 18. Nh1
h3 19. gxh3 Nh5 {Black is already slightly better because of White's spoiled
pawn structure and misplaced h1-knight.}) 17. e4 c5 ({Serious attention
deserves} 17... dxe4 18. fxe4 Ba6 {White has managed to open the f-file for
his rook but Black has created pressure against White's central pawns. The
position is about equal.}) 18. e5 Nd7 19. f4 Nxd4 20. Nxd4 cxd4 21. Qxd4 Ba6
22. Bb2 $6 ({Probably, White should have put additional pressure on d5 by
playing} 22. Rd1 {The game may continue} Bc4 23. Bd3 b5 24. Bxc4 bxc4 25. Be3
$1 $16 {[%csl Rd5] White's advantage is considerable.}) 22... Bg7 (22... Bxf1
23. Rxf1 (23. e6 $5 Nf6 24. exf7+ Kxf7 25. Rxf1 Bg7 26. f5 g5 27. Bb3 {White
has sufficient compensation for the exchange because of the ackward position
of Black's king.}) 23... Bg7 24. Bb3 Nf8 $11 {Certainly, White has
compensation for the exchange but nothing more.}) 23. Rfe1 (23. Rfd1 $1 Bc4 24.
Bd3 $16) 23... Bc4 24. Ne4 Ba2 25. Rbd1 Nxe5 26. fxe5 dxe4 27. Bxe4 Rb8 (27...
Qxd4+ 28. Bxd4 Rab8 $11) 28. Bc6 Qxd4+ 29. Bxd4 Red8 {The endgame is equal.
The weak e5-pawn is compensated by the weakness on b6.} 30. Bf2 Rxd1 31. Rxd1
Bxe5 32. b5 Be6 33. Re1 f6 34. Bg3 Kf7 35. Bxe5 fxe5 36. Rxe5 Rd8 37. Re4 Rd1+
38. Kf2 Rd2+ 39. Ke3 Ra2 40. Kd4 Rc2 41. Kd3 Ra2 42. Kd4 Rc2 1/2-1/2

