1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Nge2 d5 6. a3 Bd6 {This provocative
move has a solid positional background. Black accepts the structure which
arises after 7.c5. White's main problem is connected with the difficulty to
activate the c1-bishop which remains behind the pawn chain. The practice has
shown that the Black's idea to exchange the light-squared bishops by means of
b7-b6 followed by a7-a5 and Ba6 is very decent. At the same time, after 7.cxd5,
Black is very well prepared for the Carlsbad pawn structure in which the
bishop is better placed on d6 than on e7.} 7. Ng3 {We follow the same strategy
as in the line 5...Re8 6.a3 Bf8 7.Ng3. With his last move, White prefers to
keep a flexible pawn structure in the centre. Later on, after developing his
pieces, he could consider the e3-e4 advance.} c5 {This is by far the most
logical continuation. Black makes use of the fact that being on g3, White
knight doesn't control the centre. Black hopes that in the arising positions,
the isolated queen's pawn in his camp will be compensated by an active piece
play.} ({The continuation} 7... c6 {is dealt with in my comments to the game
Fier,A - Georgiev,Ki, Skopie, 2015}) ({Another popular alternative is} 7... b6
{Black prepares the development of his queenside by means of Bb7 and Nbd7.
Later on, he could gradually start preparing the c7-c5 pawn advance.} 8. cxd5 {
White clarifies the situation in the centre and prevents Black from playing
dxc4 in the future.} exd5 9. Be2 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gb2b4,Gd1b3,Ga3a4,Gb4b5,Gc1a3]
White's idea is to finish the development as soon as possible. In the future,
White could consider going for active actions on the queenside by playing
b2-b4, Qb3, a3-a4 followed by Ba3 and b4-b5. In such kind of positions, the
exchange of the dark-squared bishops is one of the main positional ideas for
White. Note that in a number of positions, Black's c7-pawn will be an
important weakess.} Re8 10. O-O Bb7 11. b4 c5 $6 {This move was played in the
game Peralta - Diaz, 2015. Nevertheless, this idea seems dubious to me since
Black creates an isolated pawn on d5 and opens the b-file for White's rook.} ({
Better is} 11... g6 12. Bf3 h5 13. h3 {With a complicated position. In the
future, after provoking the c7-c6 advance by means of Qb3, White could open
the centre by playing e3-e4.}) 12. bxc5 bxc5 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Rb1 Bc6 15. Nf5
Qa5 16. Nb5 Nbd7 17. Nbd4 {White has managed to take the control over the key
d4-square. Now he is going to exchange at least one of the Black's bishops and
will obtain a bishop pair. White is already slightly better.}) 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9.
b4 Be7 {The move 9...Bb6 is examined in the next game.} 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Bd3 {
We have reached a typical position with an IQP. As we know, the side playing
with such a pawn tries to organize an attack on the kingside. In this concrete
position, however, White g3-knight prevents Black from developing an
initiative on the kingside. Furthermore, White is planning to increase the
control over the d4-square by playing Nce2 followed by Bb2. On the other hand,
given the fact that White has already played the move b2-b4, Black will try to
make use of the weakened c4-square. In order to do this, he could consider the
maneuvers Nc6-e5 or Nd7-b6 followed by Be6 and Rc8.} Nc6 {This is the main
move. Black not only prepares the advance d5-d4 but at the same time is ready
to play Ne5.} ({Serious attention deserves} 11... a5 {when the game may
continue} 12. b5 Nbd7 13. Bb2 Nb6 {[%cal Gc8e6] As we have already explained,
Black's idea is to follow with Be6, Nc4 and Rc8. At this point, I recommend
the following sequence:} 14. Nce2 {[%csl Ge2,Gg3][%cal Ge2f4]} Nc4 15. Bc3 Be6
16. O-O Rc8 17. Nf5 Bxf5 18. Bxf5 {I think that White could claim a slight
edge in this position. He has a pair of bishops and a full control over the
important d4-square. Moreover, in the future, Black will have some problems to
defend the d5-pawn. Also, we shouldn't underestimate the fact that White could
use the potential of his bishops in order to create some activity on the
kingside. I don't consider the c4-square to compensate all White's advantages.}
) 12. Nce2 {This move is quite typical for the variation. White not only
prevents the d5-d4 advance but at the same time intends to take the control
over the a1-h8 diagonal by means of Bb2. Note that in positions where Black
couldn't go for d5-d4, White could consider attacking the d5-pawn by playing
Nf4.} Ne5 ({Maybe a little bit more precise would have been} 12... a5 13. b5
Ne5 {when White could transpose to the game Fier - Parligras, 2014 which is
examined below.}) 13. Bb2 {White wants to develop his pieces as quickly as
possible. In such kind of positions , we usually allow the exchange Nxd3 since
there are good central squares for our knight. After castling and putting his
rooks on d1 and c1, White could consider attacking the d5-pawn by means of Nf4.
} Nxd3+ {I am inclined to believe that this natural move makes White's task
easier.} ({Black's most principled try seems to be} 13... Nc4 {when the game
Fier - Parligras continued} 14. Bc3 a5 15. b5 Bg4 16. h3 Bxe2 {This exchange
is favourable for White. Now he has a powerful pair of bishops and full
control over the light-squares. The f5-square is expecially important because
of the possibility to play Nf5.} ({More to the point was} 16... Be6 {when after
} 17. O-O Re8 18. Nf4 Rc8 $14 {White could follow with} 19. Ngh5 {[%cal Gd1f3,
Gf3g3] This is a typical attacking idea. If White manages to exchange the
f6-knight under favourable circumstances, black king will be quite vulnerable.
Additionally, White is planning to put even more pressure against black king
by means of the maneuver Qf3-g3. Moreover, the exchange of minor pieces is
advantageous for us even from a positional point of view. We know that in the
endgame, the IQP could be rather weak. In my analysis, I didn't find a clear
way to the equality for Black. For example, in case of} g6 {White has at his
disposal the powerful} 20. Qf3 $1 {White has managed to concentrate all his
forces on the kingside. It seems that Black is already in a serious trouble.
At this point, probably the most tenacious move is} Nd7 ({The attempt to win
an exchange by means of} 20... Nxh5 21. Nxh5 d4 ({If} 21... f5 {White just
protects his c3-bishop by means of} 22. Rfc1 $1 {In a long-term, Black's
weakened kingside must tell.}) 22. Bxd4 Nd2 {doesn't work because of the
weakened dark squares in Black's camp. After} 23. Qf4 Bg5 24. Qe5 f6 25. Qg3
Nxf1 26. Rxf1 $40 {[%cal Gh3h4] followed by h3-h4, White's attack is very
dangerous.}) ({Black couldn't accept the sacrifice because White is winning
after the following forced sequence:} 20... gxh5 $2 21. Nxh5 Nxh5 22. Bxh7+ $1
Kf8 (22... Kxh7 $2 23. Qxh5+ Kg8 24. Qh8#) 23. Qxh5 {[%cal Gh5h6]} Bg5 24. h4
Nd6 25. Bd4 Bxh4 26. Qh6+ Ke7 27. Qxh4+ Kd7 28. Bf6 $18 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Ga3a4]
}) 21. Nxd5 Bxd5 22. Qxd5 Ndb6 23. Qxd8 Rexd8 24. Bxc4 gxh5 25. Bxa5 Nxc4 26.
Bxd8 Rxd8 {With a clear advantage for White. White rook is ready to invade
Black's camp.} 27. Rfc1) 17. Qxe2 Nxa3 {This is the point. Black has accepted
the exchange of his light-squared bishop in order to win a pawn. Nevertheless,
White's initiative looks quite dangerous.} 18. O-O (18. Bxf6 $2 Bb4+ 19. Kf1
Qxf6 $17) 18... Bb4 19. Bd4 {White has more than enough compensation for the
sacrificed pawn. His powerfull bishops are looking at Black's kingside, while
the knight is ready to enter the attack via f5-square. Black is already in
danger.} Re8 20. Rfc1 Bf8 21. Qf3 {This position was reached in the
abovementionned game Fier, A - Parligras, M. Instead of the dubious 22.Rc3?!,
White should have played} ({Again, very strong is} 21. Nh5 $1 {exchanging the
main defender of the black king. The game might continue} Nxh5 22. Qxh5 g6 23.
Qf3 Re6 24. b6 $1 {[%cal Gc1c7] creating the threat of 25.Rc7. Futher analysis
show that Black couldn't prevent White from developing his initiative. This
exchange sacrifice seems to be Black's only reasonable reaction. Nevertheless,
White retains considerable advantage.} Rxb6 ({The idea to cover the c7-square
with the bishop by playing} 24... Bd6 {doesn't work very well. For example,
after} 25. g3 Nc4 26. Rxc4 dxc4 27. Bxc4 Qe7 28. Bxe6 fxe6 29. Rd1 $16 {
White has a huge advantage because of the weakened black king and the active
white pieces.}) 25. Bxb6 Qxb6 26. Qxd5 Rd8 27. Qe4 $16 {Black doesn't have
sufficient compensation for the exchange.}) ({Another reasonable idea is} 21.
b6 {I think that after} Nc4 22. Bxc4 dxc4 23. Qxc4 Re6 24. Qc7 {White has a
considerable advantage since he controls the c-file and creates pressure
against the weak pawns on a5 and b7.}) 21... Re6 22. Ne2 Bd6 23. b6 $16 {
White an obvious attention.}) 14. Qxd3 a5 15. b5 Be6 16. O-O Re8 17. Nf4 Qd7
18. Rad1 {White has managed to create a considerable pressure against the weak
d5-pawn. Now Black shoud be very carefull in order to keep the ballance. At
this point, he played which is dubious. In such kind of positions, black rooks
belong to d8 and c8 squares. At least one of the rooks should control the open
c-file.} Rad8 ({Better was} 18... Red8 19. e4 {This is the most direct attempt
to fight for an advantage.} ({Another option was the positional} 19. Rd2 Rac8
20. Rfd1 Qc7 21. h3 $14 {White has an advantage due to his better pawn
structure. Nevertheless, the fight is still ahead.}) 19... dxe4 20. Qe2 Qe8 21.
Nxe6 fxe6 22. Nxe4 Rxd1 23. Rxd1 Nd5 {White retains a slight advantage because
of the weakend e6-pawn but Black keeps good defensive resources.}) 19. a4 {
White protects the b5-pawn and now, under favourable circumstances, he could
transfer his queen to the kingside.} Rc8 $6 {After this move, Black loses at
least a pawn. White immediately strikes in the centre} 20. e4 {Sega chernite
gubjat naj malko peska i izpadat v po tejka pozicija.} Red8 ({The lesser evil
was} 20... d4 21. Nxe6 Qxe6 22. Bxd4 $16 Rc4 {Despite the fact that Black is
clearly worse here, he has still some chances of counterplay. In some cases,
he could take the a4-pawn.}) 21. Bxf6 Bxf6 22. exd5 {White is already winning.
He is a pawn up while his knights are clearly better than opponent's bishops.}
Qc7 23. Qf3 Bd7 24. d6 Qb8 25. Nd5 Be5 26. Ne7+ Kf8 27. Nxc8 Bxc8 28. Qh5 Bxd6
29. Qxh7 f6 30. Nh5 1-0

