1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Nge2 d5 6. a3 Bd6 7. Ng3 c5 8. dxc5
Bxc5 9. b4 Bb6 {This move is more ambitious than 9...Be7. Black's idea is to
keep the control over the d4-square. Later on, he could proceed with Nc6
followed by d5-d4, thus going for a central strategy. As we are going to see,
Black could go for the d5-d4 break without playing Nc6 first.} 10. Bb2 d4 {
Quite a logical decision. After exchanging a pair of central pawns, Black
secures the d4- square for his bishop.} ({Another logical move is} 10... Nc6 {
This move is complitely in the spirit of the position. Black continues to
develop his pieces and is ready to accept a position with IQP. At the same
time, he keeps the possibility to play d5-d4 at a later stage.} 11. Be2 Qe7 {
[%cal Gf8d8] This move is a preparation for IQP. Black intends to proceed with
Rd8, thus supporting his pawn and creating an opposition along the d-file.} ({
After} 11... d4 12. exd4 Bxd4 13. O-O e5 {We transpose to our main line.}) 12.
cxd5 Rd8 13. d6 $1 {Remmember this idea. Given the fact that White is
underdeveloped and couldn't establish a firm control over the d4-square, he
avoids the isolated pawn which arises after 13...exd5. Istead, he prefers to
enter a symmetric pawn structure where his peaces will be much more active.
Black has difficulties to bring his light-squared bishop into play while White
is always ready to overtake the initiative by means of Qc2 and Nce4. The play
may continue} Rxd6 14. Qc2 Bd7 15. Nce4 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Rd5 17. O-O Rc8 18. Qb3 {
1/2-1/2 Wallis,C-Kazhgaleyev,M/Sydney AUS 2015/The Week in Chess 1053 (64)
White has slight but lasting advantage. The most important factor is the
activity of the minor pieces of both sides. White has a centralized knight and
his bishops has a lot of potential. On the other hand, black d7-bishop is
passive while the dark-squared bishop is restricted by the e3-pawn.
Additionally, black knight closes the way of Rc8 and Bd7. Despite these
problems, however, Black keeps considerable chances for a draw since his
position is rather solid.}) 11. exd4 Bxd4 12. Be2 e5 13. O-O Nc6 {This is by
far Black's most popular choice. Before starting any active operations, Black
prefers to complete the development.} ({Nevertheless, very interesting was} 
13... Be6 $5 {[%cal Ga7a5] Black's idea is to play a7-a5 followed by the
exchange of a pair of rooks. Later on, Black is planning to create pressure
against the c4-pawn. Here, I recommend the following sequence} 14. Qc2 a5 15.
Rfd1 ({Dubious is} 15. b5 $6 Nbd7 16. Rad1 Rc8 $11 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Ge6c4,
Gc8c4] When Black manages to create a strong pressure against the c4-pawn.})
15... axb4 16. Nb5 $1 {I like this concrete approach to the position. The idea
of this move is to create an isolated pawn on d4 which will be very weak in
the endgame. In some cases, White hopes of an advantage will be connected with
his bishop pair.} ({After} 16. axb4 Rxa1 17. Bxa1 Qc8 $11 {Black enjoys a
comfortable equality.}) 16... Nc6 17. Nxd4 Nxd4 {This is Black's most solid
continuation.} ({In case of} 17... exd4 18. axb4 Nxb4 19. Qb3 Rxa1 20. Bxa1 Nc6
21. Qxb7 $14 {[%csl Ga1,Rd4,Ge2] White has small advantage because of the
bishop pair and the weak d4-pawn. Also, we should note that black c6-knight
lacks stability.}) 18. Bxd4 exd4 19. axb4 Rxa1 20. Rxa1 Qd7 21. h3 Rd8 22. Rd1
{Despite the reduced material and the active black pieces, White could still
create some difficulties for his opponent. The d4-pawn needs protection, while
White could try to make use of his pawn majority on the queenside. In some
cases, he could consider transferring his queen to the kingside. In this line
of thoughts, the maneuver Qd2-g5 is to be considered.}) 14. Qc2 Ng4 $6 {
By making this seemingly agressive move, Black wastes time and give White the
initiative.} ({More precise is} 14... Be6 {In this case, I recommend you to
develop your pieces and go for a long-term play.} 15. Rad1 Qe7 16. Rfe1 Rfd8
17. h3 Rac8 (17... a5 18. b5 Nb8 19. Bf3 $16) 18. Nf5 Qf8 19. Bd3 {White
retains some advantage but Black is near to the equality. White wants to
provoke the move g7-g6 after which he could go for Nxd4 followed by Qa4, thus
trying to prove that the pair of bishop could be a long-term advantage.}) 15.
b5 Ne7 16. h3 {This move is too passive.} ({Better was} 16. Rad1 {White brings
his rook into play without losing time on moves like h3. The game may continue}
Nf6 17. Nce4 Nxe4 18. Qxe4 $16 {White is clearly better. He has queenside pawn
majority and enjoys a dangerous pin along the d-file.}) 16... Nh6 ({Black
should have complicated the matters by going for the following forced sequence
} 16... Nxf2 17. Rxf2 Bxf2+ 18. Kxf2 Qd4+ 19. Ke1 Qh4 20. Qd3 Nf5 21. Nce4 Rd8
22. Qf3 Be6 {This position is very complicated. White has two pieces for a
rook and pawn but his king is unsafe.}) 17. Rad1 Nef5 18. Nxf5 Nxf5 19. Bd3 Nh4
20. Be4 f5 21. Bd5+ Kh8 22. Rxd4 $1 exd4 23. Ne2 {White's advantage is quite
obvious. The powerfull pair of bishops and the pawn up gives White a
sufficient compensation for the missing exchange.} f4 24. Nxd4 Qg5 25. Kh2 Rb8
26. Rg1 Bd7 27. Ne6 $2 (27. Qc3 $18) 27... Bxe6 28. Bxe6 Rbe8 29. Bd5 Re7 30.
Bd4 b6 31. Qd3 Ng6 32. Rd1 Nh4 33. Rg1 Rfe8 34. Bc3 (34. Bc6 $1 Rf8 35. Bc3 Re6
36. Bd5 Ree8 $11 {This position is already about equal. White has sufficient
compensation for the exchange but nothing more.}) 34... Rd8 35. Bb4 Re3 36. Qd4
Re2 37. Bd2 Ng6 ({Better was} 37... Nf5 38. Qxf4 Qxf4+ 39. Bxf4 Rxf2 40. Bc7
Re8 $15 {Black has better endgame but there are is a long way to the victory.})
38. Rf1 Ree8 39. Rd1 h6 40. a4 Re2 41. a5 Qf6 42. Qxf6 gxf6 43. axb6 axb6 44.
Bc3 Ne5 45. Bd4 Rd6 46. Ra1 Rd2 47. Ra8+ Kg7 48. Ra7+ Kh8 49. Ra8+ Kg7 50. Ra7+
Kh8 51. Ra8+ 1/2-1/2

