1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 {The game was played in the last round of Skopie
open 2015. In order to share the first place, I needed to win with Black
pieces against the strong Brazilian grandmaster. That's why I gave preference
to the Nimzo-Indian Defence which leads to complicated positions which are
rich of possibilities.} 4. e3 O-O 5. Nge2 d5 6. a3 Bd6 7. Ng3 c6 {This move is
not so passive as it seems at first sight. After playing Nbd7 on the next move,
Black is planning to go for dxc4 followed by e6-e5. The arising positions are
very complicated and requite deep positional understanding from both sides.} 8.
Be2 Nbd7 9. O-O dxc4 10. Bxc4 e5 11. Ba2 {White moves his bishop to a safer
position. Now, in a number of variations, White could play Nf5, interrupting
the coordination in Black's camp.} Nb6 {This move is necessary. Black should
cover the important f5-square.} 12. dxe5 Bxe5 13. Qc2 {We have reached a
typical pawn structure - White has pawn majority on the kingside, while Black
has majority on the queenside. In general, such kind of positions are
favorable for the side with a kingside majority when the queens are on the
board. The reason is quite simple. By moving forward his central pawns, White
gains a lot of space and has chances to create threats against black king. On
the other hand, in the endgame, Black could create an outside passed pawn
which would be very dangerous.} Qe7 14. Nce2 {Quite a reasonable decision.
White is gradually preparing the advance of his central pawns. Under favorable
circumstances, White could go for e3-e4 followed by f2-f4 and e4-e5. Another
important point is that now the e1-a5 diagonal is open for White's
dark-squared bishop. Depending on the circumstances, this bishop could go
either on c3 or b4.} Re8 {Black is fighting against White's central strategy.
Neverheless, I don't consider this move to be the optimal solution for Black.}
({Black should have challenged the active a2-bishop by playing} 14... Be6 $1 {
The game may continue} 15. Nf5 Bxf5 16. Qxf5 Rad8 {We have reached a very
complicated position. Black controls the open d-file and his pieces are active.
On the other hand, White has a number of useful moves at his disposal. For
example, he could proceed with moves like Qc2, Rb1, Bd2 and eventually even
b2-b4. In the future, he could even obtain an advantage due to the bishop pair.
}) 15. e4 Bc7 16. Bb1 {[%cal Gc1d2,Gd2c3,Gf2f4] Very interesting idea. From b1,
the bishop not only protects the central pawn but at the same time after f2-f4
and e4-e5 creates threats along the b1-h7 diagonal.} Nbd7 {With this move I
offered a draw but my opponent refused.} 17. Bd2 Qc5 18. Bc3 Be5 19. Kh1 Ng4
20. Bxe5 Qxc2 21. Bxc2 Ndxe5 22. h3 Nf6 23. b3 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ge4e5,Gg3e4,
Ge4d6] Black has managed to exchange the queens but White's pieces are much
more active. At the same time, he could increase the pressure by playing f2-f4
followed by e4-e5 and Ng3-e4-d6. White is already a little bit better.} b6 24.
f4 Ng6 25. e5 Nd5 26. Be4 $1 Ba6 $1 27. Bxd5 cxd5 28. Rf2 {[%cal Ge2d4]} Bxe2 {
This exchange is necessary because if white wanted to place his knight on d4.
In such case, black light-squared bishop will not have any targets.} 29. Nxe2
Rac8 30. Ra2 Rc5 31. Rd2 Ne7 32. Rf3 g6 33. Rfd3 Rec8 34. g4 a6 35. Kg2 Kf8 {
White will have strong central knight but Black could create counterplay along
the open c-file.} 36. Nd4 Rc1 37. f5 gxf5 38. gxf5 Re1 39. Nf3 {After this
move my opponent offer a draw. I accepted. The position is already equal.}
1/2-1/2

