1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Nge2 d5 6. a3 Be7 {This is by far
Black's most popular choice in this position. Despite the fact that on
e7-square the bishop is more passive, Black has better control over the
important d5-square and White couldn't exectute the c4-c5 advance with a tempo.
If White doesn't clarify the position in the centre by playing 7.cxd5, Black
could play either c7-c5 immediately or go for a Carlsbad setup by playing
c7-c6 followed by Nbd7.} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {Played in a Grunfeld style. Black gives
the centre in order to attack it later. This modern approach to the position
became very popular recently. The main move 7...cxd5 is dealt with in the next
games.} 8. Bd2 {White gradually develops his pieces by making usefull moves.
Another idea behind the move 8.Bd2 is to take with the bishop in case of 8...
Nxc3. Given the fact that the dark squared bishop is restricted by white
centra pawn chain, White could also consider the exchange of the dark-squared
bishops via the b4-square.} Nd7 9. g3 {Another patient and solid continuation.
The idea behind it is quite simple. White wants to develop his light-squared
bishop on g2, thus creating a strong pressure along the h1-a8 - diagonal.
Given the fact that the c8- bishop is not developed yet, Black must play very
precisely in order to solve thi problem. That's why his most natural reaction
is} b6 {[%cal Gc8b7] Intending to meet 10.Bg2 by means of 10...Bb7.} ({Serious
attention deserves the alternative} 9... N5b6 {[%cal Ge6e5] with the idea 10...
e6-e5. The critical position arises after the moves} 10. Bg2 e5 ({Less logical
is} 10... c5 {In such kind of positions, it's extremely difficult for Black to
neutralize the g2-bishop. A possible continuation could be} 11. O-O Nf6 12.
dxc5 Bxc5 ({The "active"} 12... Nc4 {doesn't manage to spoil the coordination
in White's camp.} 13. Bc1 {[%csl Rc4] It turns out that the c4-knight is very
unstable. In a number of positions, White could activate his dark-squared
bishop by playing b2-b3 followed by Bb2. It's not clear how Black will develop
his light-squared bishop.} Bxc5 ({The endgame arising after} 13... Qxd1 14.
Rxd1 Bxc5 15. b3 Nb6 16. Bb2 {[%cal Ga1c1] Followed by Rac1 is extremely
difficult for Black.}) 14. Qc2) 13. Qc2 Be7 14. Rfd1 Rb8 15. Ne4 {With a
dangerous initiative for White.}) 11. O-O exd4 12. Nxd4 Ne5 {[%csl Rc4,Rd3]
Black is fighting for the weakend c4 and d3-squares. At the same time he could
restrict the activity of the g2-bishop by means of c7-c6. In the games that
were played so far, Black has managed to create an adequate counterplay. At
this point, my suggestion is} 13. Nce2 $146 {According to my database, this
move is a novelty. White wants to clear the way of his d2-bishop which could
be relocated to c3 or a5, depending on the circumstances. At the same time,
the e2-knight could go to f4, taking d5-square under control. A possible
continuation could be} c5 14. Nf3 Nxf3+ 15. Bxf3 Qc7 16. Nf4 Bd7 17. Ba5 $14 {
White enjoys a slight but lasting advantage. He has a better pawn structure
and controls the d5-square.}) ({The same strategy could be followed even in
case of} 9... N5f6 {For example} 10. Bg2 e5 11. O-O exd4 12. Nxd4 Ne5 13. Nce2
$5 {works in the same way.}) ({Rememmber that the exchange} 9... Nxc3 {is
advantageous for White since he could activate his dark-squared bishop.} 10.
Bxc3 c5 {As we have seen in some of the abovementionned lines, after the c7-c5
advance, Black has problems to deal with the pressure along the h1-a8 -
diagonal. After} ({The attempt to neutralize White's pressure along the
long-diagonal doesn't work very well in this concrete position. After} 10... b6
11. Bg2 Rb8 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gc7c5] White could go for} 12. Qa4 {White queen
creates pressure on the queenside and frees the d1-square for his rook.} a5 {
[%cal Gc8a6] Black is planning to develop his light-squared bishop via a6.
Nevertheless, Black's last move leads to further weaknesses on the queenside.}
({White retains some pressure even in case of the more solid} 12... Bb7 13.
Bxb7 Rxb7 14. Qc6 Qc8 15. O-O Nb8 16. Qf3 {[%cal Ge3e4,Gf1d1,Ga1c1,Ge2f4]
Later on, White will place his rooks on d1 and c1 and go for Nf4 followed by
e3-e4.}) 13. O-O Ba6 14. Rfe1 c5 15. Rad1 {White has managed to establish a
considerable pressure.}) 11. Bg2 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nf6 13. O-O Nd5 {I have came up
with a new idea.} 14. Rc1 $146 {White brings his rook into play and intends to
opt for the following pawn sacrifice} Bf6 15. Qb3 Nxc3 16. Rxc3 Bxd4 17. exd4
Qxd4 18. Rd1 Qe5 19. Qc2 {[%cal Gc3c7] With the idea to invade Black's camp by
playing Rc7. White controls the entire board, while Black couldn't develop his
pieces.}) 10. Nxd5 {This move plays an important role in White's plan. The
idea is to weaken Black's pawn structure. For example, if in the future Black
plays c7-c5, White could play dxc5, creating hanging pawns in Black's camp
which could be vulnerable.} exd5 11. Bg2 Bb7 {This logical move is by no means
Black's only option. Sometimes, Black prefers to develop his bishop via
f5-square.} ({An alternative is} 11... Nf6 12. O-O Bf5 13. Bb4 $1 {As we are
going to see from the main line, this is quite a typical idea for such kind of
positions. We have already mentioned that White tries to exchange his passive
dark-squared bishop.} a5 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Rc1 h6 {This position was reached
in the game Martinovic, S - Papp, G. Here, instead of 16.Nc3, I suggest} 16.
Qa4 {[%cal Gc1c3,Gf1c1,Ge2f4] followed by doubling the rooks along the c-file.
Usually the knight goes to f4 from where it attacks the d5-pawn.}) 12. Bb4 $1 {
This typical and logical move turns out to be a novelty in this position. The
World Champion Magnus Carlsen demonstrates an excellent positional
understanding.} Nf6 ({White is not afraid of the doubled pawns which arise
after} 12... Bxb4+ 13. axb4 {The game might continue} Qe7 14. Qb3 a6 15. O-O
Nf6 16. Rfc1 $14 {[%cal Ge2f4,Gf4d3] White's advantage is out of question. His
rooks are well placed on the semi-open files "a" and "c". Note that Black
couldn't play c7-c5 and will be always tied to the defense of the c7-pawn.
Later on, White could further improve his position by playing Nf4-d3.}) 13. O-O
Re8 ({Serious attention deserves} 13... c5 14. dxc5 bxc5 15. Bc3 {We have
reached a typical middlegame position with hanging pawns. White minor pieces
are excellently developed and at some point, Black's central pawns could be
vulnerable.} Ne4 {This move is quite logical. By putting his knight in the
centre, Black tries to reduce the pressure against the d5-pawn.} 16. Nf4 {
Despite the fact that there are is still a lot of fight, I think that White's
chances are preferable.}) 14. Rc1 c6 15. Bxe7 Rxe7 16. Re1 Qd6 17. Nf4 Bc8 $6 {
This move seems to be dubious.. Even though Black's desire to activate his
light-squared bishop is understandable, with his last move he weakens the
c6-pawn. Now Black's major pieces will be tied to the defense of the weak
c6-pawn.} ({Instead, it was possible to gain some space on the queenside by
playing} 17... a5 {Even in this case, however, White keeps pressure after} 18.
Qb3 Qd8 19. Red1 $14 {Black's counterplay is far from being clear.}) 18. Qa4
Rc7 ({In case of} 18... Bd7 {White could play} 19. Qb4 Qxb4 20. axb4 $16 {
White keeps a considerable advantage in the endgame. He could improve his
position either by b4-b5 or by the maneuver Nf4-d3-e5. The c6-pawn is very
weak.}) 19. f3 Be6 $6 20. e4 {White has taken the control over the centre and
is planning to go for the e4-e5 advance. On the other hand, there are is no
coordination in Black's camp.} dxe4 21. fxe4 Qd7 22. d5 $1 {This is the
beginning of a forced variation which allows White to enter an advantageous
ending.} cxd5 23. Qxd7 Rxd7 24. Nxe6 fxe6 25. Bh3 {This is the point! White
will win back the sacrificed pawn. It's not difficult to see that white bishop
dominates black knight.} Kh8 {This move loses on the spot.} ({More tenacious
would have been} 25... Re8 {Nevertheless, after} 26. exd5 Rdd8 27. Bxe6+ Kf8
28. Rc7 Re7 29. Rec1 $18 {WIth an easy win. White is a pawn up and his bishop
is clearly stronger than black knight.}) 26. e5 Ng8 27. Bxe6 Rdd8 28. Rc7 d4
29. Bd7 {Black resigns since the d-pawn will be lost. At the same time,
White's passed pawn is unstoppable.} 1-0

