1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Nge2 d5 6. a3 Be7 7. cxd5 exd5 {
This is Black's main continuation. He opens the c8-h3-diagonal for his bishop
and intends to go for a Carlsbad type of positions after c7-c6. Black's hopes
are connected to the fact that White's c1-bishop is closed by his central pawn
chain. On the other hand, white knight could occupy the active f4-square.
Additinally, White's flexible pawn structure allows him to develop initiative
in the centre and on the kingside.} 8. Nf4 {We have reached one of the main
positions for the entire variation. Instead of the text move, White has played
a number of continuations here - 8.b4, 8.Ng3, 8.g3 and even 8.h3. So far,
Black proves sufficient counterplay in every single variation. By placing his
knight on f4-square, Black temporarily stops the c7-c5 advance. Now he is
ready to develop his bishop to d3, taking under control the important
e4-square.} Re8 {The idea of this move could be explained by the fact that for
the moment Black doesn't want to clarify the position of his c-pawn. Depending
on the position, he could go either c7-c6 or c7-c5. At the same time, the rook
goes to e8 in every case.} ({The main alternative is} 8... c6 9. Bd3 Bd6 {
After protecting the d5-pawn, Black could improve the position of his bishop.}
({Another very interesting plan is based on the advance of the queenside pawns.
} 9... a5 10. O-O Na6 {Another flexbible move. Before going for active actions
on the queenside, Black want's to improve the position of his knight. After
playing Nc7, depending on White's plan, he could play c6-c5 or b7-b5.} ({
More straightforward approach is} 10... Re8 11. f3 b5 {We are following a
remarkable strategical battle. In response to White's central strategy, Black
organizes a counterplay on the queenside. The critical position arises after
the moves} 12. Bc2 Ba6 13. Re1 b4 14. Na4 Nbd7 15. e4 Nf8 16. e5 N6d7 {This
position arised in the game Rasmussen,A - Polgar, J, 2012. Here, White wasted
time by playing} 17. Nh5 {With his last move White not only wastes a valuable
time but at the same time allows the typical c6-c5 advance.} ({Before going
for active kingside opearations, White should have completed the development.
After} 17. Be3 Bb5 (17... Nb6 18. Nxb6 Qxb6 19. Qd2 $14) 18. Qd2 $14 {The
position is complicated but White is a little bit better. The e5-pawn gives
White a spatial advantage in the centre and the possibility to organize a
kingside attack.}) 17... g6 18. Ng3 c5 {After this typical central strike,
Black creates a dangerous central passed pawn.} 19. dxc5 Nxc5 20. f4 Bc4 21.
Be3 Qc7 22. Qd2 $2 {This move is already an important mistake.} ({White should
have played} 22. Nxc5 Bxc5 23. Kh1 Bxe3 24. Rxe3 {Despite the fact that
Black's position is still preferable, White has some counterplay based on the
f4-f5 advance in a suitable moment.}) 22... b3 23. Nxc5 bxc2 24. b3 ({White's
only chance was} 24. b4 f6 25. Qxc2 fxe5 26. f5 {Black is a pawn up and he has
a strong centre. Nevertheless, there are still some technical difficulties.})
24... d4 $1 25. Qxd4 Bxc5 26. Qxc5 Qxc5 27. Bxc5 Bxb3 28. Ne4 Rec8 $17 29. Rac1
Ne6 30. Be3 Rd8 31. g4 Rd1 32. Kf2 Rad8 33. Nd6 f6 34. f5 fxe5 35. Nb7 Rf8 36.
Nxa5 Ba4 37. Bh6 Nc5 38. Ke2 Rfd8 39. Nc4 Nd3 {0-1 Rasmussen,A-Polgar,J/
Istanbul TUR 2012/The Week in Chess 931}) 11. f3 Nc7 {[%cal Gc6c5] Black
protects his d5-pawn and prepares the c6-c5 advance. As a rule, in this
variation, Black always intends to counter the move f2-f3 by means of c6-c5.}
12. Bd2 c5 13. dxc5 {This is by far the most logical continuation. Black was
ready to go for a queenside pawn expansion by means of c5-c4 followed by
b7-b5-b4.} Bxc5 14. Kh1 Ne6 15. e4 $1 {Right decision from a positional point
of view. White opens the centre in order to make use of his more active pieces.
The game So, W - Van Wely, L went} dxe4 16. Nxe4 Bd4 17. Qc2 h6 ({Better was} 
17... Nxf4 18. Bxf4 Nxe4 19. Bxe4 Qf6 20. Rad1 Qxf4 21. Rxd4 Bf5 {Where
White's advantage is by no means huge.}) 18. Rad1 {1-0 So,W-Van Wely,L/
Hoogeveen NED 2013/The Week in Chess 989 (42) Now Black has problems to
develop his pieces in a comfortable way. White could already claim a slight
advantage.})) 9. Bd3 c6 ({If Black is really determined to avoid the lines
including the c7-c6 advance, he could go for the move} 9... Bd6 {The critical
position arises after the moves} 10. O-O ({A mistake is} 10. Nfxd5 {in view of}
Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Qg5 $17 {[%csl Rd5,Rg2][%cal Gg5d5,Gg5g2]}) 10... Bxf4 11. exf4
Nc6 12. Be3 Ne7 {[%cal Gc8f5] Black has managed to create doubled pawns in
White's camp. Later on, his play will be based on the restriction of the
activity of White's bishops. As we can see, White's e3-bishop is already
restricted by the pawns on f4 and d4. At this moment, Black prepares the move
Bf5 with the obvious idea to exchange the light-squared bishops. On the other
hand, White has enough ressources to prevent such an exchange. Furthermore,
White's kingside pawns could move forward, thus gaining a considerable amount
of space. In such case, White could increase the activity of his bishop pair.}
13. Qc2 {This move is played with the idea to prevent 13...Bf5. At the same
time, White would be happy to play f4-f5 followed by f2-f3 and g2-g4, gaining
space and restricting the mobility of black minor pieces.} g6 14. f3 {[%cal
Gg2g4] Creating space for the e3-bishop and at the same time preparing the
g2-g4 advance. Of course, Black's most principled continuation is} h5 {This
move was played by Sergei Karjakin in his game against Wesley So from Bilbao
2016.} ({Less precise is} 14... Bf5 {This move allows Black to immediately
exchange the light-squared bishops but allows the g2-g4 advance.} 15. g4 Bxd3
16. Qxd3 {Later on, White could follow with Rae1, Kg2 and eventually Bf2 - h4 
(g3). White's dark-squared bishop will become active while black knights are
restricted by White's kingside pawns. Note that in such kind of positions, the
e5-square is perfect for White's rook.}) 15. Qd2 {Clever move. White intends
to meet 15...Bf5 by means of 16.Be2. The game So - Karajkin saw} Bf5 16. Be2
Qd7 17. Rfe1 Be6 18. Bf2 Nf5 19. Bd3 Nd6 20. Re5 {[%cal Gh2h3,Gg2g4,Ga1e1]
White is slightly better in this position. His plan is very simple - the
position could be improved by means of Rae1 followed by h2-h3, g2-g4 and Bh4.
On the other hand, Black's plan is far from being clear.}) 10. O-O Nbd7 11. f3
{White's idea is to take the important e4-square under control. Later on, his
idea is to execute the e3-e4 pawn advance.} Nf8 {This is Black's best
continuation. Black opens the way of his c8-bishop and wants to activate his
knight via e6 or g6.} 12. Bd2 Ng6 13. Nfe2 $1 {[%cal Gg1h1] We have reached a
very instructive moment. White rightly avoids the exchange of the knights
since such an exchange will make Black's defensive task much easier. In the
future, White is planning to play Kh1 followed by Be1-f2 and e3-e4.} c5 {
Another good move. Black not only gains space on the queenside but at the same
time radically prevents the e3-e4 advance.} 14. Rc1 b6 15. Be1 Bf8 16. Bf2 Bb7
17. Qd2 {White has finally established a perfect coordination between his
pieces. Now he is ready to develop a kingiside initiative by playing g2-g4.
Pay attention to the fact that Black couldn't organize a central counterplay
in this position. That's why he should gain space on the queenside.} Qd7 {
It's clear that Black underestimates White's attacking resources on the
kingside.} ({He should have immediately created a queenside counterplay by
means of} 17... c4 18. Bc2 Bc6 {[%cal Gb6b5]} 19. Ng3 {[%cal Ge3e4] Now the
e4-pawn is not hanging and White is going again for the e3-e4 central advance.}
b5 20. e4 dxe4 21. Ngxe4 Nxe4 22. Bxe4 Bxe4 23. fxe4 Qd7 {Despite the fact
that I still prefer White's position because of the strong pawn centre, we
should admit that the queenside pawn majority gives Black an adequate
counterplay. Further tests are requited for the right evaluation of this
position.}) 18. g4 cxd4 19. exd4 {We have reached a typical pawn structure
which is favorable for White. White has more active pieces and space advantage
on the kingside. He could develop his kingisde initiative in a flawless way
since Black has no counterplay at all. The b7-bishop is very problematic in
such kind of positions.} a6 20. Bf5 Qd8 21. h4 Bd6 22. h5 Nf8 23. Nf4 h6 $6 {
This move further weakens Black's kingside.} ({Better was} 23... g6 {Even in
this case, however, White keeps the initiative after} 24. hxg6 hxg6 25. Bb1 Ne6
26. Nxe6 Rxe6 27. Kg2 $14 {[%cal Gf1h1] followed by Rh1.}) 24. Bh4 Qb8 25. Nd3
N8h7 26. Rfe1 {This move gives Black an important chance.} ({Better was} 26.
Rce1 $1 {after which the move} Ne4 $2 {is wrong because of} 27. fxe4 Bg3 28.
Bxh7+ Kxh7 29. Bf6 Bxe1 30. Qxe1 gxf6 31. Rxf6 Kg8 32. e5 $18 {and White is
winning.}) 26... Rxe1+ ({At this point, Black missed an excellent tactical
possibility:} 26... Ne4 $3 27. fxe4 Bg3 28. e5 Bxh4 29. Rf1 Nf8 {When White's
advantage is only minimal. Black could establish a blockade on the dark
squares.}) 27. Rxe1 Qc7 28. Kg2 Rf8 29. Nb4 $16 Qb8 30. Qd3 Qa8 31. Nc2 Ng5 32.
Qd2 Ngh7 33. Re2 Qb8 34. Re1 Bf4 35. Qd3 Ng5 36. Ne2 Bd6 $2 {Thi is the
decisive mistake after which Black loses a pawn and the game.} (36... Bc8 37.
Bxc8 Rxc8 38. Nc3 $16) 37. Bxg5 hxg5 38. Qd2 Nh7 39. Bxh7+ Kxh7 40. Qxg5 $16
Qd8 41. Qxd8 Rxd8 42. Nc3 Rc8 43. Kf2 a5 44. Re2 Ba6 45. Rd2 Bf4 46. Ne3 Bb7
47. Re2 Rd8 48. Nf5 Bc8 49. Ne3 Be6 50. Rc2 Rc8 51. Ncd1 Rb8 52. Ng2 Bg5 53.
Kg3 Bf6 54. Rd2 b5 55. Nf4 b4 56. a4 Bd7 57. b3 Be7 58. Nxd5 Bd6+ 59. Kf2 Be6
60. N1e3 Rd8 61. Rd3 Rb8 62. Nc4 Bxd5 63. Nxd6 Rb6 64. Ne4 f6 65. Nc5 Kg8 66.
Kg3 Kf7 67. f4 Rb8 68. Re3 Rd8 69. g5 fxg5 70. fxg5 Ba8 71. Rd3 Bd5 72. Kf4 Bc6
73. Rd2 Rd5 74. Ne4 Rd8 75. Rd3 Ke6 76. Ng3 Rf8+ 77. Kg4 Kd5 78. g6 Bb7 79. Kg5
Ba6 80. Re3 Kxd4 81. Re7 Kc3 82. Rxg7 Kxb3 83. h6 Ka3 84. h7 Bc4 85. Rc7 1-0

