1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Nge2 c6 {This strange looking move
became quite popular recently. Black is planning to transfer his bishop to c7
and later follow with d7-d5. In such case his dark-squared bishop will be very
active on the b8-h2 diagonal while white c1-bishop will be restricted by it's
own pawns.} 6. a3 Ba5 7. c5 {I think that thos rare continuation is White's
best bet for an advantage in this position. White's reaction is very
principled since Black has a backward pawn on d7. In order to complete his
development, Black should play d7-d5, allowing the exchnage of his central
pawn after cxd6. Later on, if Black wants to bring his light-squared bishop
into play by means of e6-e5, the central pawn will be exchanged and White will
enter a position with central pawn majority.} d5 {This is the only reasonable
reaction.} ({In case of} 7... Bc7 {White's most solid continuation seems to be}
8. g3 {restricting the activity of the c7-bishop and preparing the move Bg2.} (
{Interesting is the attempt to punish Black for the delay of the d7-d5 advance
by playing} 8. e4 {White controls the centre while Black has difficulties to
complete the development of his pieces. A possible line could be} e5 9. dxe5
Bxe5 10. f4 Bc7 11. e5 Ne8 12. Ng3 b6 13. Be3 bxc5 14. Qf3 d6 15. Rd1 Qh4 16.
exd6 Nxd6 17. Be2 Re8 18. O-O Bg4 19. Qxg4 Qxg4 20. Bxg4 Rxe3 21. Bf3 $14 {
when White has more than sufficient compensation for the pawn thanks to his
better developed pieces.}) 8... d5 ({After} 8... e5 $5 9. Bg2 d6 10. cxd6 Qxd6
11. O-O Rd8 12. Qc2 Nbd7 13. d5 Nb6 14. dxc6 bxc6 15. Rd1 $14 {White enjoys a
slight but lasting advantage because of the weak c6-pawn.}) 9. cxd6 Bxd6 10.
Bg2 e5 11. O-O Nbd7 12. h3 Qe7 ({To similar positions leads} 12... Re8 13. Qc2
Qe7 14. e4 $14 {when White is ready to exchange the central pawns and go for
the typical central expansion by playing f2-f4 followed by e4-e5.}) 13. Qc2 a5
14. e4 $1 Re8 15. f4 $1 $16 exd4 16. Nxd4 Bc5 17. Be3 Nb6 18. Bf2 {White's
pawn centre gives his a lot of space and room for maneuvers. Black has
difficulties to create counterplay since his pieces are badly placed.} a4 19.
Rac1 Be6 20. Nxe6 fxe6 21. e5 Nfd5 22. Ne4 Bxf2+ 23. Qxf2 Rf8 24. h4 g6 25. Bh3
h6 26. Nc5 Rf5 27. Qd4 Kh7 28. Rf3 Raf8 29. Bxf5 gxf5 30. Rc2 Ra8 31. h5 Ra5
32. g4 fxg4 33. Rg3 {1-0 Dolezal,C-Cori Quispe,K/Buenos Aires ARG 2014}) 8.
cxd6 Qxd6 9. b4 Bb6 {The bishop has nothing to do on the a7-g1 - diagonal.} ({
More precise was} 9... Bc7 {Black's idea is that in some cases the
construction Qd6 + Bc7 could be used in order to create some threats against
the white king. For example. if White develops his pieces by playing Ng3
followed by Bd3 and 0-0, Black could go the the h7-h5-h4 advance.} 10. g3 {
This move is designed to restrict Black's activity along the b8-h2 - diagonal.
After finishing the development by playing Bg2 and 0-0, White could consider
going for a queenside activity by means of Qc2, Rb1, Rd1 and eventually b4-b5.
In such kind of positions, the b4-b5 pawn contact is very useful because it
allows White to increase the potential of his g2-bishop.} e5 11. Bg2 Nbd7 12.
O-O Nb6 {Black wants to make use of the weakened c4-square. Such an idea could
be very annoying if white dark-squared bishop is already developed on b2 or on
d2. Of course, White is not obliged to hurry up with the development of his
bishop.} 13. Qc2 Bg4 14. h3 exd4 15. Nxd4 Bh5 16. a4 $1 Bg6 17. Qb3 $14 {
[%cal Gc1a3] White has an excellent position. Besides the typical b4-b5, he
threatens to play a5-a6, thus spoiling Black's queenside position. Pay
attention to the fact that in some cases the move Ba3 could be very annoying
for Black.}) 10. Bb2 Nbd7 11. g3 a5 12. b5 $1 {White manages to execute this
typical idea at an early stage.} e5 ({In case of} 12... cxb5 13. Bg2 {White
wins back the pawn since} b4 {doesn't work in view of} 14. axb4 $16 {with a
huge advantage for White.}) 13. dxe5 Qxe5 14. Bg2 Qe7 ({White keeps the
advantage even in case of} 14... Ng4 15. O-O Nxf2 16. Rxf2 Bxe3 17. Qf1 $14)
15. O-O Ne5 16. bxc6 bxc6 17. Na4 {White obtained considerable positional
advantages - he created an weakness on c6 and his pieces are much more active.
Black's counterplay is mainly based on different tactical threats.} Ba7 18. Qc2
Ba6 19. Rfd1 Rad8 $6 ({Only chance was} 19... Neg4 $1 {Here, White could go
for the following forced sequence} 20. Nd4 Nxe3 21. Nxc6 Qe8 22. fxe3 Qxe3+ 23.
Kh1 Ng4 24. Rd2 (24. Nxa7 Nf2+ 25. Qxf2 Qxf2) 24... Rfe8 25. Qd1 Be2 26. Rxe2
Qxe2 27. Qxe2 Rxe2 28. Nxa7 Rxa7 29. Kg1 Rae7 30. Bc3 $14 {White has a slight
advantage, but there are is still a lot of fight.}) 20. Nd4 c5 21. Nf5 Qc7 22.
Nxg7 $3 {Decisive tactical shot which complitely destroys Black's kingside. My
opponent was so shocked that he entered a terrible time trouble.} Bd3 $8 {
This is the only move.} (22... Kxg7 23. Qf5 Rxd1+ 24. Rxd1 Rd8 25. Bd5 $18) 23.
Qc3 ({White is probably winning even after the exchange sacrifice after} 23.
Rxd3 Rxd3 24. Nf5 Rfd8 25. h3 c4 26. Rf1 $16 {Nevertheless, I have decided to
go for an ending where I have a pawn up and a better structure.}) 23... Kxg7
24. Qxe5 Qxe5 25. Bxe5 Bc2 26. Rxd8 ({Stronger was} 26. Rdc1 $1 Bxa4 27. Rc4
Rd1+ 28. Rxd1 Bxd1 29. Rf4 $18 Re8 30. Bxf6+ Kf8 31. Bc3 $18 Bb3 32. Bxa5 {
and White is winning.}) 26... Rxd8 27. Nc3 (27. Nb2 $1 Bb3 28. Rc1 $18) 27...
Bb8 28. Bxf6+ Kxf6 29. Rc1 Rd2 30. Be4 $6 ({To a simple win leads} 30. Ne4+
Bxe4 31. Bxe4 {And White wins a second pawn.}) 30... Bb3 31. Bf3 Kg7 32. Ne4
Ra2 33. Nxc5 Rxa3 34. Rb1 (34. Nxb3 Rxb3 35. Bc6 $18) 34... Bc4 $1 35. Rc1 Bb5
36. Bd5 Be5 37. Kg2 Rc3 $1 38. Rxc3 Bxc3 39. Bb3 Bb4 40. Ba4 Bc4 41. Nb3 Bd5+
42. f3 Bxb3 43. Bxb3 f5 44. f4 Bc5 45. Kf3 h5 46. Ba4 h4 47. Bd7 hxg3 48. hxg3
Kg6 49. Ba4 Bb4 50. Bc2 Kf6 51. e4 fxe4+ 52. Kxe4 Bd6 53. Kf3 Bc7 54. g4 Bd6
55. g5+ Kg7 56. Kg4 Bc7 57. Kf5 Bd6 58. Ba4 Bc7 59. Ke4 Bd6 60. f5 Be7 61. Kf4
Bd8 1/2-1/2

