1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 b6 {This is a very interesting system.
Black prefers to keep his central pawn structure flexible. Depending on the
circumstances, his light-squared bishop could go either to b7 or to a6. For
example, after spoiling White's structure by means of Bxc3, Black could play
Ba6 followed by an attack against the c4-pawn.} 5. f3 {By playing this move,
White is planning to occupy the centre by means of e3-e4. White makes use of
the fact that Black couldn't play 5...d7-d5 due to 6.Qa4.} Nh5 {Black is
trying to stop e3-e4. By creating the threat of Qh4, he wins a tempo to play
f7-f5.} ({If} 5... O-O {then} 6. e4 $1 {White takes the control over the
centre.} Ba6 (6... Nh5 7. Nh3 f5 {is very well met by:} 8. Bg5 Qe8 {In this
position, I found a nice novelty} 9. Be2 $5 $146 {With the threat of f3-f4} ({
Another option is} 9. e5 $5 $146 {Strong novelty, White is threatening Be2
followed by f3-f4, thus attacking the h5-knight.}) 9... Nc6 10. e5 f4 11. Qd2
d6 12. a3 Bxc3 13. Qxc3 h6 14. Bh4 g5 15. Bf2 Ng7 16. O-O $14 {White is
slightly better.}) ({The try to counterattack in the centre is not good here.
White manages to keep his powerful central pawns.} 6... d5 7. e5 Nfd7 8. cxd5
exd5 9. f4 c5 10. a3 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Ba6 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Nf3 Rc8 (13... b5 14.
f5 Qb6 15. O-O Rfe8 16. Kh1 $16 {1-0 (34) Aleksandrov,A (2577)-Moiseenko,A 
(2648) Almaty 2016}) 14. Qd3 Nc7 15. f5 $14 {1-0 (29) Papa,S (2397)-Jenni,F 
(2517)/Biel 2004}) 7. Bd2 $5 {in my opinion White needs to avoid the formation
of doubled c-pawns in case of} (7. Bg5 h6 8. Bh4 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 d6 $13 {The
position is very complex . As usual in this structure Black wants to block the
position and organize an attack against the c4-pawn. On the other hand, White
attacks on the kingside. The question is who will succeed first!? I do not
like this approach, because it gives Black a clear plan.}) 7... Nh5 8. Nh3 f5 {
deserves attention} 9. Bd3 $146 ({wrong is} 9. e5 $2 Qh4+ 10. g3 Qxd4 11. Qe2
d5 12. exd6 Qxd6 13. Bg2 Nc6 $19 {Black is winning in the game: 0-1 (22)
Degtiarev,E (2372)-Gavrikov,V (2500)/ Germany 2005}) 9... fxe4 (9... Nc6 10.
Qa4 Bb7 11. O-O) 10. Bxe4 Qh4+ ({better is} 10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 d5 12. Bd3 Bxc4
13. Bxc4 dxc4 14. O-O {With a better position for White.}) 11. Nf2 Nc6 12. Qa4
Bb7 13. O-O Bd6 14. Nh3 {White has an advantage due to the control of the
centre and his most active pieces.}) (5... c5 {The most challenging option!
The arising positions are typical for Benoni defence, Saemish variation.} 6. d5
O-O ({In case of} 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 O-O 8. e4 d6 {We reach a very complicated
position. White has a pair of bishops and strong pawn centre, but his doubled
pawns give Black a typical Nimzo-Indian counterplay against the c4-pawn. The
important nuance is that Black's knight can't reach the a5-square and Black
can't open c-file. These considerations make Black's counterplay not so
dangerous. In my opinion White has better chances here.} 9. Bg5 {White's plan
is to play Bd3, Ne2 and start pushing pawns on the kingside.} h6 10. Bh4 exd5
11. cxd5 Nbd7 12. Bd3 Re8 13. Ne2 a6 14. a4 {White is much better here.} Ne5
15. Bc2 Ng6 16. Bf2 {White has space advantage and many plans for improving
the position: one plan is to push pawns on the kingside, another is to attack
the pawn on b6. Black has no real counterplay. 1-0 (88) Aleksandrov,A (2615)
-Arshaev,A (2152) Minsk 2015}) 7. e4 Re8 (7... b5 $1 {this move leads to an
extremely sharp game.} 8. e5 {the most challenging move.} exd5 9. exf6 d4 10.
a3 Ba5 11. b4 dxc3 12. bxa5 {We reach this position almost by force after 8.e5.
White is a piece up, but his king is in danger and he didn't develop a single
piece. Nevertheless, White should obtain an advantage with an accurate play.}
Re8+ 13. Kf2 Qxf6 14. Qd5 c2 15. Ra2 Bb7 {It looks like White is in trouble,
but he is not forced to take the bishop.} 16. Qd2 bxc4 17. Rxc2 d5 18. Bb2 d4 (
18... Qd8 19. Nh3 {I can't see any concrete threats here and prefer to play
this position with White.}) 19. Bxc4 Nd7 20. Bb5 Ne5 21. Rxc5 {I believe that
everything is a home preparation of both players, but it looks like that
Brazilian GM (who is a famous theoretician) was better prepared.} Ng4+ 22. Kg3
{White king is safe here.} Ne3 23. Nh3 Re5 24. Rxe5 Qxe5+ 25. Kf2 Qxb5 26. Qxd4
{Now the storm is over and it is clear that White is a bit better here.} Nf5
27. Qb4 {I believe that White is better here. Re1 is coming, the bishop on b2
is much more active that the one on b7. 1/2 (26) Fier,A (2624)-Navara,D (2735)
Drancy 2016}) 8. Nge2 exd5 ({Serious attention deserves Black's try to attack
the pawn on c4 by} 8... Ba6 {0-1 Kantsler,B (2474)-Soffer,R (2459)/Herzliya
2009/(40)} 9. Ng3 d6 10. Bf4 $5 (10. Be2) 10... exd5 11. cxd5 Bxf1 12. Kxf1
Bxc3 13. bxc3 {White has a tiny advantage due to his strong centre and the
bishop on f4 which puts pressure on d6.}) 9. cxd5 d6 (9... Bb7 {Usually the
bishop is not very well placed on b7 in all Benony type of positions.} 10. Kf2
{Interesting idea to evacuate the king and get rid of the nasty pin on the
e-file.} d6 11. Ng3 Nbd7 12. a3 Ba5 $2 ({better was} 12... Bxc3 13. bxc3 a6 14.
Be2 Ne5 15. a4 Bc8 16. Re1 $14 {White finished the development and has an
advantage due to his pair of bishops and the space advantage in the centre.})
13. Nb5 Nf8 14. Nf5 Re5 15. Nbxd6 Bxd5 16. Bf4 $18 {1-0 Milov,V (2622)-Amin,B 
(2635)/Dubai 2014 (27)}) 10. Ng3 Nbd7 11. Be2 a6 12. a4 Nf8 {This move is a
bit passive} ({even after the best} 12... Ne5 13. O-O Bd7 {White is still
better after:} 14. f4 Ng6 15. f5 Ne5 16. Bg5 {White keeps the initiative.}) 13.
O-O Ng6 14. Na2 {Nice move with the idea to open the queenside with b2-b4} Ba5
15. Rb1 Bd7 16. b4 cxb4 17. Nxb4 Bxb4 18. Rxb4 b5 19. axb5 axb5 20. Kh1 $14 {
White is clearly better in the game: 1-0 Milov,V (2595)-Ovetchkin,R (2483)/
Moscow 2002 (46)}) 6. Nh3 f5 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O Nc6 9. Ne2 {[%cal Ga2a3]
Remember this manoeuvre! White does not allow the exchange on c3 and intends
to follow with a2-a3.} ({The move} 9. Qc2 $5 {also deserves attention} Nf6 10.
Ne2 Be7 11. a3 a5 12. Bd2 $14 {With an advantage. White develops his pieces
naturally. He has a lot of useful moves to make like: Rae1, Bc3, e4. In that
time Black's pieces seem strange developed and It is not obvious what is
Black's plan. 1-0 Ernst,S (2589) -Heinemann,T (2484)/Germany 2010}) 9... Be7 {
We reached a Dutch type of position. White's chances seem preferable due to
the control of the central squares and athe possibility to attack on the
kingside.} 10. g4 {This is an extremely concrete approach.} (10. a3 {Was
another option which also gives White an edge.}) 10... fxg4 11. fxg4 Nf6 ({
To a better play for White leads} 11... Rxf1+ 12. Qxf1 Nf6 13. g5 Nh5 14. Qg2
$14) 12. Ng3 {White starts an attack on the kingside. The threat is g5,
followed by Qh5.} g6 13. Bd2 e5 {This move just weakens the position of the
black king.} ({but even after the best} 13... Bb7 14. g5 Ne8 15. Qc2 {White
has a crushing attack!}) 14. g5 Ne8 15. Rxf8+ Bxf8 16. Qf3 Bg7 (16... exd4 $2 {
loses immediately} 17. Rf1 Qe7 18. c5 $1 {[%cal Gd3c4]} Bg7 19. Nf4 $1 Bb7 $140
20. Bc4+ Kh8 21. Nxg6+ hxg6 22. Ne4 $18 {[%cal Gf3h3]}) 17. Be4 ({the
strongest move was} 17. Nh5 $1 $146 gxh5 $140 $2 ({The best chance for Black
is:} 17... d5 $5 18. cxd5 Bxh3 19. Qxh3 Qxg5+ 20. Kh1 Qxh5 21. Qxh5 gxh5 22.
dxc6 exd4 23. Bc4+ Kh8 24. exd4 Bxd4 25. Bf4 $16 {White has an advantage in
this endgame despite the missing pawn. The pair of bishops is very strong and
the threat Rd1-d7 is hard to be met.}) 18. Qd5+ Kh8 19. Qe4 $18 {With mate in
a couple of moves.}) 17... Rb8 $2 (17... Ba6 $1 {gives Black chances to
survive.} 18. Bd5+ Kh8 19. Bc3 exd4 20. exd4 Rb8 $13 {Black has some
counterplay.}) 18. Rf1 Qe7 19. Nh5 $1 {Now the game is over} gxh5 20. Qxh5 Nf6
21. gxf6 Bxf6 22. Bd5+ Kh8 23. Rxf6 Qg7+ 24. Ng5 {1-0 Ovod,E (2395)-Cmilyte,V 
(2470)/ Sochi 2006} 1-0

