1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 c5 {This is by far the Black's most solid
alternative to the main line. Besides his normal plan based on the fight for
the centre by means of d7-d5, in this position, Black has another idea as well
- he could follow with Bxc3 and later play against White's doubled pawns on
the c-file. That's why I recommend} 5. Nge2 {White's main idea is to take the
bishop pair without allowing our opponent to spoil our pawn structure. At this
point, White is ready to follow with a2-a3. Black has a variety of options
here.} d5 {Black is delaying castling and trying to put pressure against the
centre.} (5... b6 $5 {This unusual variation is quite playable for Black. My
recommendation here is} 6. a3 Ba5 7. Rb1 $1 {White is threatening b2-b4,
forcing Black to put his Knight on a6-square.} Na6 8. Ng3 Bb7 9. f3 {Without
this move we can't finish the development.} O-O 10. Bd3 d5 {Black is in a
hurry to open the position until White hasn't finished the development.} ({
After} 10... cxd4 11. exd4 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 d5 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Qc2 Rc8 15. Bd2
{White has a tiny edge due to his pair of bishops and the awkward position of
Black's knight on a6. 1/2 (39) Zoubkov,A (2411)-Petkov,S IECC email 2012}) 11.
O-O cxd4 12. Nb5 $3 {Fantastic move, renewing the threat b2-b4} dxc4 (12...
dxe3 $2 {is losing a piece} 13. b4 $18) 13. Bxc4 Rc8 14. Qe2 {It is obvious
that Tomashevsky was very well prepared for the opening. I can't find equality
here. White's position is just better. 1-0 (63) Tomashevsky,E (2728)-Caruana,F
(2787) Wijk aan Zee 2016}) (5... Ne4 {This move has no independent value
because it usually transposes to the 5...cxd4} 6. Bd2 Nxd2 7. Qxd2 cxd4 8. exd4
d5 9. c5 {transposes to 5...cxd4} a5 (9... Qf6 {The idea of this rare move is
to meet g2-g3 by means of Qf6-f3.} 10. a3 Ba5 11. f4 $1 Bd8 12. g3 {I like
White's position a lot. The plan is to finish the development and to start
pushing our queenside pawn majority. It is not obvious what Black should do.
1-0 (21) Gavrikov,V (2555)-Shishkov,A (2270) /Parnu/Tallinn 1998}) ({Dubious is
} 9... Qd7 10. a3 Ba5 11. g3 Bd8 12. b4 $1 {Black couldn't create a
counterplay.}) ({Dangerous is} 9... b6 10. a3 Bxc3 11. Nxc3 bxc5 12. dxc5 a5
13. Bb5+ Bd7 14. O-O {When Black will have hard time to fight against White's
queenside passed pawns.1-0 (30) Karsa,L (2385) -Dory,J (2340)/Budapest 1982/
(41)}) 10. a3 Bxc3 11. Nxc3 a4 12. Rc1 O-O 13. Be2 Bd7 14. O-O Nc6 {1/2 (31)
Le,Q (2697)-Vitiugov,N (2725) Baku 2015} 15. Nb5 $146 {White should be
slightly better here. The knight will go to d6 while the a4-pawn could be weak
in some moments.}) ({After} 5... O-O 6. a3 $1 {We win a pair of bishops
without ruining our pawn structure.} Bxc3+ 7. Nxc3 cxd4 8. exd4 d5 9. c5 {
Strong move which does not allow Black to take on c4 and to keep some
counterplay against the isolated d-pawn. Now White's plan is simple: develop
the pieces and start pushing his queenside majority.} Nc6 {Black does not
allow Bd3 and puts pressure on the d4-pawn.} (9... b6 {this move can't pose
any trouble for White} 10. b4 bxc5 11. dxc5 e5 12. Bg5 Bb7 13. Nb5 $5 {The
Knight is coming on d6} ({possible is} 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Qxd5 e4
{1-0 Khismatullin,D (2656)-Harutjunyan,G (2464)/ Izhevsk 2011/(33)} 16. Rc1 Nc6
17. Be2 Rad8 18. Qc4 $14 {with a clear edge for White.}) 13... d4 14. Nd6 Bd5
15. f3 h6 16. Bh4 Nc6 17. Bd3 $16 {White was much better in the old game 1/2
Colle/Rubinstein - Landau/Tartakower/ Rotterdam 1932/}) 10. Be2 Ne4 11. O-O
Nxc3 12. bxc3 b6 13. a4 {[%cal Gc1a3] Even that the position is very complex,
I prefer White here due to the powerful pair of bishops and the protected
c-pawn which can be a very important factor in a near future.}) 6. a3 {The
idea is to achieve a pair of bishops without doubling our pawns, If we delay
this move, then Black can take on d4 and then return the bishop on e7 or d6.}
Bxc3+ ({If} 6... Ba5 {then we can enter a favorable ending by playing} 7. dxc5
dxc4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Bd2 {I like White's position a lot. It seems to me that
White is better developed and easily can put pressure against Black's
queenside. Also, Black's king's position on d8 gives us a lot of tactical
motifs.} e5 {Black is trying to solve the problem with his queenside by
freeing the e6-square for his bishop.} (9... Nbd7 10. Ng3 Nxc5 11. Bxc4 Bc7 12.
O-O a6 13. b4 {[%cal Gf1d1,Ga1c1,Gc4e2,Ge2f3] White rooks will come on c1 and
d1 and the bishop on f3. We should be satisfied with the opening - better
position and absolutely no risk.}) 10. Ne4 $5 {Strong reply. We are aiming to
take the c4-pawn with the knight. From there the knight will create multiple
threats and put additional pressure on the centre and the queenside. If Black
does not exchange the bishops then our knight will penetrate Black's position
via d6-square.} Nc6 11. N2g3 Bxd2+ 12. Nxd2 $1 c3 {Black is trying to spoil
our structure, which is a typical idea. The drawback of this idea is that
temporarily White has a pawn up and since Black loses time to take it back, we
will mobilize our forces. White has a serious advantage here.} 13. bxc3 $14) 7.
Nxc3 cxd4 8. exd4 dxc4 9. Bxc4 Nc6 10. Be3 O-O 11. O-O {We have reached a
typical position with an isolated queen's pawn. One real chessplayer shouldn't
be scared to enter such positions with both colours. This concrete version of
the IQP is highly advantageous for White. One of the White's knights is
exchanged for Black's dark-squared bishop. Usually, the exchange of minor
pieces favors Black, but here the absence of the dark-squared bishop causes a
lot of problems for Black. Having a pair of bishops, White could consider
opening the position by means of d4-d5. Additionally, in some positions the
pin along the h4-d8 diagonal could be quite dangerous.} h6 {This move is
played with the idea to stop Bg5. Nevertheless, White has important attacking
resources in this position. He could consider the following regrouping - Rac1,
Qf3-g3, Rfd1 with a serious chance to organize an attack against the Black's
king.} (11... b6 12. Qf3 Bb7 13. Bd3 Qd7 14. Qh3 {Black's position looks very
hard here. White's threats on the kingside look very dangerous.} Ne7 ({
decisive blunder here is} 14... Nxd4 $2 {because of the following thematic
taktical motif} 15. Rad1 e5 16. Bxh7+ $1 {1-0 Milovanovic,R (2435)-Sentic,P 
(2270)/Djakovo 1994}) 15. Bg5 Ng6 16. Bxf6 gxf6 {With a big advantage for
White after both:} 17. d5 $5 $36 {with dangerous threats} ({or the positional} 
17. Rad1 Rad8 18. Rfe1 Qc7 $2 19. Bxg6 $1 hxg6 20. Qh6 {With a winning
position in the game 1-0 (27) Aleksandrov,A (2668)-Vekshenkov,N (2462)/Sochi
2004/ (54)})) 12. Rc1 Ne7 13. Qf3 Ned5 14. Qg3 Kh8 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 ({the move} 
15... exd5 {leads to a very unpleasant and passive endgame after:} 16. Bd3 Bd7
17. Qd6 Bc6 18. Qxd8 Rfxd8 19. f3 Rac8 20. Bf4 Kg8 {Winning this position is a
matter of technique, but I believe that this is more than successful outcome
after the opening. 1-0 Onischuk,A (2652)-Vekshenkov,N (2462)/Sochi 2004/(57)}
21. Rfe1 Re8 22. Kf2 $14) 16. Bxd5 Qxd5 17. Rc5 Qe4 18. Bd2 {'!'} b6 19. Re1
Qxe1+ (19... Qg6 20. Qxg6 fxg6 21. Rc7 $16) 20. Bxe1 bxc5 21. dxc5 Bb7 22. Ba5
{The rest is a simple technique} Rac8 23. Qd6 Bc6 24. h3 Rfe8 25. Bc7 Kg8 26.
Qxc6 Re7 27. b4 Rexc7 28. Qa6 Rb8 29. Kf1 Rbc8 30. Ke2 Kf8 31. Kd3 Ke8 32. Kc4
Rd8 33. b5 Rd2 34. c6 Rxf2 35. Qb7 Rf4+ 36. Kb3 1-0

