1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 d5 {This continuation was quite popular in
the past. Black is fighting for the centre and delays castling for later.
Later on, depending on the circumstances, Black could either exchange his
b4-bishop for the knight or go back to e7.} 5. a3 {White forces his opponent
to decide what to do with the bishop. If 5...Be7 then Black's possition is a
little bit passive. After the principled 5...Bxc3, we achieve one of the main
crossroads in Nimzo-Indian Defence. This kind of positions was the matter of
discussion even 70 years ago. White is trying to advance his pawn majority in
the centre and latter to organize an attack on the kingside while Black is
trying to block the position and prevent his opponent from playing e3-e4-e5.}
Bxc3+ (5... Be7 {Black is loses a tempo, but keeps his bishop alive.} 6. Nf3
O-O {White is at a crossroad here: the specialists in this variation GM Ivan
Sokolov and GM A. Aleksandrov choose 7.b4. Another logical developing move is
7.Bd3. I will show you both of them.} 7. Bd3 {after this move Black has a
choice between the slow development with b7-b6 followed by Bb7 and entering an
IQP-position after 7...dxc4.} (7. b4 {Aleksandrov} a5 ({after} 7... b6 8. cxd5
exd5 9. Be2 c5 10. dxc5 bxc5 11. bxc5 Bxc5 12. O-O Nc6 {White has an easier
game. Later, he could proceed with Bb2, Qc2, Rfd1 and Rac1. 1-0 (34) Graf,A 
(2643)-Lushenkov,M (2462) Cappelle-la-Grande 2009}) 8. b5 c5 9. bxc6 bxc6 10.
c5 {The position is very close to equal, but I still prefer to be White here,
the space advantage on a queenside, potential weaknesses on c6 and a5 and the
open b-file give White enough ideas to play for a win. 1/2 (50) Sokolov,I 
(2645)-Lazarev,V (2387) Al Ain 2014}) 7... b6 (7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 c5 9. O-O Nbd7
({after} 9... cxd4 10. exd4 {We reach one of the main tabias in the IQP
positions. I will not explain in details how to play in such kind of
structures, because I need to make another database. For those who are
interested GM Gavrikov and GM Grigorov have wonderful articles on this topic
in Modern Chess Magazine! For now, I will limit myself to saying that White's
long-term plan is based on an attack against the opponent's king. A possible
setup is Bg5, Qd3, Rad1 followed by the maneouvre Ba2-b1, creating dangerous
threats against the Black's king.}) 10. e4 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Ne5 12. Be2 Bd7 13.
Be3 Nc6 14. Rc1 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 Bc6 16. Qd3 {With a slight advantage for White
due to his more active pieces. 1-0 (44) Milov,V (2690)-Kortschnoj,V (2598)
Baku 2008}) 8. O-O Bb7 9. cxd5 exd5 10. b4 Nbd7 11. Qb3 {White develops his
queen and stops c7-c5. His plan is to continue with a3-a4, Ba3 and to exchange
the bishops by means of b4-b5. The ideal pawn structure on the queenside will
be a4-b5 against a7-b6-c7 when the pawns on a7 and c7 are weak.} a6 12. a4 Bd6
({bad is} 12... c5 $2 13. bxc5 bxc5 14. Qxb7 Rb8 15. Qxa6 Ra8 16. Qb5 Rb8 17.
Qa6 Ra8 18. Bxh7+ Kxh7 19. Qd3+ {White has decisive material advantage. 1-0 
(29) Neverov,V-Vignesh,N/New Delhi IND 2014}) 13. Ba3 {[%cal Gb4b5]} Qe7 14.
Bf5 c6 15. Nd2 Rfe8 16. Rfe1 {White is better and can choose between 2
possible plans: to prepare e3-e4 or to prepare b4-b5 with advantage in both of
the cases.} g6 17. Bh3 $14 {1-0 Brodsky,M (2527)-Bruned,B (2227)/Metz 2010/ 
(30)}) 6. bxc3 O-O (6... c6 {This move was popular recently, mainly because of
the efforts of the Chinese players. The main idea is to stabilize the
situation in the centre and to prepare the move e5.} 7. a4 $1 {The best move
here. White will activate his bishop via a3.} O-O 8. Nf3 b6 9. cxd5 exd5 10.
Bd3 Ba6 11. O-O c5 12. Ne5 Re8 13. a5 Bxd3 14. Nxd3 Nc6 15. axb6 axb6 16. Rxa8
Qxa8 17. dxc5 bxc5 18. Nxc5 {1-0 (39) Caruana, F (2805)-Hou,Y (2676) Dortmund
2015}) 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Bd3 c5 9. Ne2 {This is by far White's best option.
White is planning to play 0-0, f3, Ra2-e2, Rfe1 and e3-e4 in an appropriate
moment. Black is trying to exchange the light squared bishops via a6 after
which he could consider stopping e3-e4 by doubling the rooks the on e-file.} b6
(9... Nc6 10. O-O Re8 11. f3 b6 {The drawback of this move order is that now
White can save the pair of bishops and then is easier to prepare e3-e4.
Usually, the rule in this type of positions is that If White manages to carry
out the e3-e4 advance, then he is much better.} 12. Ng3 Bb7 13. Ra2 Rc8 14. Re2
cxd4 $6 {This move makes White's task much easier.} ({More tenacious is} 14...
h5 $1 {Black starts a typical play against White's g3-knight. Even in this
case, however, White keeps an edge after} 15. Rfe1 $14) 15. cxd4 Na5 16. Kh1 $1
Nc4 17. e4 $1 Nd7 (17... dxe4 18. fxe4 Qxd4 $2 19. e5 {[%cal Gd3h7]} Red8 20.
exf6 Qxd3 21. Re8+ Rxe8 22. Qxd3 {1-0 La Manna, A (2199)-Messina,R (1897)/
Otranto 2011/(24)}) 18. e5 g6 19. f4 {After taking the control over the centre,
White has a free hand to organize an attack on the kingside. Also, it's
important to mention that the potential of White's bishop pair is very high.}
Qh4 {very strong is} ({The move} 19... f5 {doesn't help either} 20. Nxf5 $5 ({
White can win without this sacrifice as well.} 20. exf6 Nxf6 21. f5 Ne4 22.
fxg6 hxg6 23. Bxe4 dxe4 24. Ref2 {White has a decisive attack. The threat is
Rf6 and Black can't hold the kingside.} e3 25. Rf6 Rc6 26. Rxc6 Bxc6 27. Qc2
$18) 20... gxf5 21. Bxf5 {White has only 2 pawns for the piece, but Black has
no defenders on the kingside and Black's position is undefendable.} Rc7 22. Bd3
Nf8 23. f5 Bc8 24. Ref2 Rf7 25. Qh5 Rg7 26. Bh6 Rc7 27. f6 Rf7 28. Rf3 Be6 29.
Rg3+ {1-0 Yilmaz, T-Skalkotas,N (2370)/Bihac 1979}) 20. Ref2 $1 Rf8 21. Nf5 $1
{Fantastic Knight sacrifice only for one pawn. The idea is to ruin Black's
pawn structure on the kingside and to activate all pieces.} gxf5 22. Bxf5 Rfd8
23. Rf3 Nf8 24. Bxc8 (24. Rg3+ Kh8 25. Bxc8 Rxc8 26. f5 $18 {And there is no
good way to meet Bg5!}) (24. Rh3 Qe7 25. Qh5 $18) 24... Bxc8 25. f5 $18 Ng6 26.
fxg6 fxg6 27. Rf4 Qe7 28. Rf6 Qg7 29. Qe1 Bf5 30. Qh4 Rc8 31. Bh6 Qd7 32. e6
Qe8 33. R1xf5 {Wonderful game 1-0 Gurevich,M (2435) -Agzamov,G (2590)/Riga
1985/URS-ch}) 10. O-O Ba6 11. f3 {A multi purpose move which restricts the
f6-knight and prepares e3-e4.} Re8 12. Ng3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nc6 14. Bb2 Rc8 ({
Another interesting idea is} 14... h5 $5 {Black's idea is to met e4 with h4
and to take the pawn on e4. The other continuation is} 15. Rae1 $5 (15. e4 $3 {
The beginning of the very deep idea.} h4 16. Nf5 {In the game Black quickly
goes wrong and finds himself in a lost position after:} g6 ({Critical is:} 
16... dxe4 17. fxe4 cxd4 ({If} 17... Rxe4 {then} 18. Nxg7 $3 Ne5 19. Qh3 cxd4
20. cxd4 Nc4 21. Nf5 Nxb2 22. Qb3 {With multiple threats}) 18. cxd4 Rxe4 19.
Nh6+ gxh6 20. Rxf6 Qxf6 21. Qxe4 {Black has a pawn up, but White can try to
exploit the weak position of Black's king. White's play seems much easier to
me.}) 17. Nxh4 dxe4 18. fxe4 Nxe4 19. Rf4 Qe7 20. Nxg6 Qg5 21. Rxe4 Rxe4 22.
Qxe4 Qxg6 23. Qe2 $18 {1-0 (34) Navara,D (2735)-Sturua,Z (2548) Gjakova 2016})
15... h4 16. Nf5 h3 17. gxh3 (17. g4 g6 18. Ng3 {The position is very complex,
but it seems that Black has good chances due to the pawn on h3 and the idea
Nc6-a5-c4.}) 17... Ne7 18. dxc5 Nxf5 19. Qxf5 Rc8 20. cxb6 Qxb6 21. Rf2 Rc5 {
Black has enough compensation for the sacrificing material due to multiple
weaknesses in White's camp}) (14... c4 $6 {This move is considered dubious.
Very good example for White's play is the following game.} 15. Qd2 Qd7 16. Rae1
{White's play is very logical. Kasparov improves the position of all his
pieces. Then he is ready to play e3-e4 and start a crushing attack.} h5 17. e4
g6 18. Bc1 Nh7 19. Qh6 Re6 20. f4 {The break f5 is coming.} Ne7 21. f5 gxf5 22.
Qxh5 dxe4 23. Nxf5 Nxf5 24. Rxf5 Rae8 25. Re3 Rg6 26. Rh3 {Fantastic attacking
game by the young G.Kasparov 1-0 (26) Kasparov,G (2690) -Ivanovic,B (2515)
Niksic 1983}) 15. Rae1 {the possibility to realize e3-e4 gives White better
prospects} (15. Rad1) 15... Na5 $5 {Black's best try here} ({the move} 15... h6
{is too slow} 16. e4 cxd4 17. cxd4 dxe4 18. fxe4 Ne5 19. Qd1 Nc4 20. Bc1 {
White has à big advantage due to his strong central pawns and his pieces are
ready for an attack on the kingside. 1-0 (29) Kotov, A-Unzicker, W/
Saltsjobaden 1952/IZT}) (15... cxd4 {also do not solve Black's problems.} 16.
cxd4 Qd7 17. e4 dxe4 18. fxe4 Ne5 19. Qe2 Nc4 20. Rxf6 $1 {And White has a
decisive attack.}) (15... Re6 {Logical move with the idea to triple major
pieces on the e-file.} 16. e4 $1 {White has no time to lose.} cxd4 17. cxd4
dxe4 $6 ({If} 17... Ne7 18. e5 Ne8 19. f4 $16 {White has a strategically
winning position. The threat is f5 followed by massive attack against the king.
}) 18. fxe4 Ne5 19. Qd1 (19. Qe2 $1 {is an improvement with the idea to meet}
Nc4 {with} 20. d5 $1 Nxd5 21. Rd1 $1 {with a winning position}) 19... Nc4 20.
Ba1 {White is clearly better here. His plan is to play d4-d5 followed by Nf5
with multiple threats. 1-0 (28) Moskalenko,V (2513)-Barrios,F (2222)/Barcelona
2002}) 16. e4 Nc4 17. Bc1 cxd4 18. cxd4 dxe4 19. fxe4 Ne5 {This is the
critical position for the line. Black's idea is to discoordinate White's
forces, and to put pressure on the d4-pawn.} 20. Qd2 $1 {Very precise move
which gives White the advantage in all the variations.} (20. Qd1 $6 Rxc1 $1 21.
Qxc1 Qxd4+ 22. Kh1 Nd3 {And Black can be optimistic for the future.}) 20... Ng6
(20... Nc4 {is well met by} 21. Qf2 Qd7 22. h3 {The last prophylactic move
before starting concrete actions .} Rf8 23. Nf5 {Now the threat is Nxg7} Ne8
24. e5 Qe6 $2 {last mistake in already lost position.} 25. d5 Qd7 26. e6 {
